		<div class="listing-header">
										<h1>General</h1>
				
						<br class="cl"/>
		</div> 
		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Modeling-water-resources-management-at-the-basin-level" title="Modeling water resources management at the basin level" alt="document">Modeling water resources management at the basin level</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
This report describes the methodology and application of an integrated hydrologic–economic river basin model. It is based on a review of state-of-the-art modeling approaches to IWRM at the river basin scale. The model is applied to the Maipo River Basin to address site-specific research questions regarding (1) the role of water rights and water rights trading in enhancing allocation efficiency; (2) the role of water use efficiency in saving water in the irrigation sector; (3) the impact of changes in physical irrigation efficiency on basin-level economic and physical efficiency; (4) the effects of hydrologic uncertainty on irrigation technology choice; and (5) the potential for substitution among water and other crop production inputs. A key conclusion is that the crop area can increase by 15%, mostly in the form of high-value crops to the detriment of annual prairie and maize, while domestic and industrial withdrawals can almost double. <a href="http://www.ifpri.org/pubs/abstract/149/rr149.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Modeling-water-resources-management-at-the-basin-level">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-and-agriculture" title="Water and agriculture" alt="document">Water and agriculture</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
Current policy and market approaches used by countries to address agricultural water issues are reviewed to contribute to important debates on how agriculture can better manage scarce water resources and provide ecosystem services. Agricultural use and impact on water resources involve highly complex trade-offs. The main challenge is to ensure that water resources used by agriculture are best allocated among competing demands. A number of issues to be addressed by policy makers are recommended, including: (1) integrating policy treatment of water and energy input use by agriculture; (2) establishing clear lines of responsibility in the institutional framework to manage water; (3) strengthening water policy reforms to allow for water pricing and trading, wan water service competition; and (4) raising the capacity of stakeholders (farmers, industry and community groups) to participate in the design and delivery of policy responses for integrated water management.<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=DKfImAqXwscC&amp;pg=RA1-PA218&amp;dq=%22water+resources%22+OR+%22water+management%22+internet+%22developing+countries%22+OR+MDGs+OR+millennium+%22reference+guide%22+OR+%22source+book%22+OR+handbook+OR+manual+date:1998-2007&amp;lr=&amp;num=100&amp;as_brr=1&amp;sig=JEDwH0pMgb8k6lwne0CYy46FC1g#PPP1,M1" target="_blank">Read the book.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Water-and-agriculture">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Irrigation-in-Africa-Europe-and-Latin-America" title="Irrigation in Africa, Europe and Latin America" alt="document">Irrigation in Africa, Europe and Latin America</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
In this update, the worldwide GIS coverage of areas under irrigation has been increased based on data collected through the Aquastat programme. For this update, a new inventory of sub-national irrigation statistics was compiled. This report describes an update of the Digital Global Map of Irrigation Areas for the continents of Africa and Europe as well as for the countries of Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, Peru and Uruguay. The reference year for the statistics is 2000. Adding up the irrigated areas per country as documented in the report gives a total of 48.8 million ha while the total area equipped for irrigation at the global scale is 278.8 million ha.<a href="http://www.geo.uni-frankfurt.de/ipg/ag/dl/f_publikationen/2006/FHP_05_Siebert_et_al_2006.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Irrigation-in-Africa-Europe-and-Latin-America">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Workshop-proceedings-on-design-and-implementation-of-capacity-development-strategies" title="Workshop proceedings on design and implementation of capacity development strategies " alt="document">Workshop proceedings on design and implementation of capacity development strategies </a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
A general overview of capacity development (CD) for agricultural water management in developing countries is presented and guidelines for the design of CD are developed. A keynote paper on CD strategies is followed by a series of case studies from Nicaragua, South Africa, Uzbekistan, Kenya, Indonesia, India and China. During the general discussions the following key issues were dealt with: (1) how to stimulate demand for CD, particularly in view of the numerous other constraints on the time of farmers, agency staff and other actors; (2) how to establish successful WUAs, taking account of the known difficulties of initiating and supporting community-level processes; (3) how to monitor and evaluate the effectiveness of CD programmes. This requires a focus on assessing the impact and outcomes of programmes, rather than simply quantifying outputs; and (4) how to upscale successful programmes to reach larger numbers of actors, whilst still keeping in view the need for context and location specific actions. This international workshop was held in Beijing and was part of a series of 4 workshops.<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/009/a0415e/A0415E00.htm#TOC" target="_blank">For more information.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Workshop-proceedings-on-design-and-implementation-of-capacity-development-strategies">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reengaging-in-agricultural-water-management" title="Reengaging in agricultural water management " alt="document">Reengaging in agricultural water management </a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The World Bank’s recent strategies for rural development, water, and environment call for a reengagement in AWM (agricultural water management). The report seeks to: (1) set out the changing context of demand and supply for agricultural water; (2) identify the policy, institutional, and incentive reform options that will accelerate productivity improvements and pro-poor growth; and (3) to articulate priorities for investment in AWM. Key messages emphasize integrated water resource management, increased water productivity, and new institutional arrangements with more say to farmers, engagement of the private sector, and a reduction of the government’s role. <a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTARD/Resources/DID_AWM.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reengaging-in-agricultural-water-management">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Shaping-the-future-of-water-for-agriculture" title="Shaping the future of water for agriculture" alt="document">Shaping the future of water for agriculture</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
The messages of this sourcebook center around the key challenges to agricultural water
management, specifically: (1) building policies and incentives; (2) designing institutional reforms; (3) investing in irrigation systems improvement and modernization; (4) investing in groundwater irrigation; (5) investing in drainage and water quality management; (6) investing in water management in rainfed agriculture; (7) investing in agricultural water management in multipurpose operations; (8) coping with extreme climatic conditions; and (9) assessing the social, economic, and environmental impacts of agricultural water investments. More and better investments in agricultural water are needed, because after decades of successfully expanding irrigation and improving productivity, farmers and managers face an emerging crisis in the form of poorly performing irrigation schemes, slow modernization, declining investment, constrained water availability, and environmental degradation.<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTARD/Resources/Shaping_the_Future_of_Water_for_Agriculture.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Shaping-the-future-of-water-for-agriculture">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Integrating-livelihoods-into-integrated-water-resources-management" title="Integrating 'livelihoods' into integrated water resources management" alt="document">Integrating 'livelihoods' into integrated water resources management</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
This paper examines the weaknesses in the current understanding of integrated water resources management (IWRM) from a livelihoods perspective. Empowering poor people, reducing poverty, improving livelihoods, and promoting economic growth ought to be the basic objectives of IWRM. But IWRM often tends to focus on second generation issues, discouraging attention to making water available to poor people for productive and domestic uses. Instead, WRM should be placed in the broader context of modern integrated natural resource management (INRM) and the livelihoods approach with effective democratic development and management of water and other natural resources. Transparent user-friendly information and models for assisting decision-making are essential features of livelihood-oriented IWRM.<a href="http://www.sarpn.org/documents/d0000575/P530_IWMI.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Integrating-livelihoods-into-integrated-water-resources-management">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reclaiming-drainage-toward-an-integrated-approach" title="Reclaiming drainage: toward an integrated approach " alt="document">Reclaiming drainage: toward an integrated approach </a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
This report presents a tool for analysis and planning in integrated drainage projects, called DRAINFRAME, the Drainage Integrated Analytical Framework. DRAINFRAME is a procedure for analyzing and assessing the functions and values embedded in a participatory planning process. The analytical component of the tool proposes 9 iterative steps for systematically mapping the functions of natural resources systems, and the exploration of the implications of particular drainage interventions. The report distinguishes 4 different levels at which the multifunctionality of resources systems can be explored: the large basin, the hydro-ecological region, the landscape, and the drainage system. The meso-level of the landscape is the most appropriate level for integrated planning of drainage interventions. Drainage interventions attempt to enhance certain functions for the benefit of these stakeholders. Institutional arrangements are created to manage these interventions. The integrated approach to drainage is a way to put the principles promoted by recent water management strategies into action. The art is to translate general strategic principles into practical “how-to” approaches to drainage.<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTARD/Resources/Drainage_final.pdf" target="_blank">Read the document.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Reclaiming-drainage-toward-an-integrated-approach">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Agriculture-food-and-water" title="Agriculture, food and water" alt="document">Agriculture, food and water</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
In this publication the role of water in global food production is examined. Subjects include: (1) the status of food production in the world; (2) the contributions from rainfed and irrigated crops; (3) the role of the market; and (4) the connection between food security and poverty. Agriculture will remain the dominant user of water at the global level. In many countries, in particular those situated in the arid and semi-arid regions of the world, this dependency can be expected to intensify. Within the current demographic context, the global food security is slowly improving and towards 2050, the increased world population could enjoy access to food for all. Agriculture can use water more efficiently than present practices indicate. As competition for limited water resources and pressure to internalize environmental impacts intensify in a number of countries, agriculture and, in particular, irrigation comes under growing pressure to review and adapt its policies and institutions, including the water rights and allocation system. Agriculture can also increase the use of recycled water and of water stemming from non-conventional sources.<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/y4683e/y4683e00.htm" target="_blank">For more information.</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Agriculture-food-and-water">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Dialogue-on-Effective-Water-Governance" title="Dialogue on Effective Water Governance" alt="document">Dialogue on Effective Water Governance</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>
During 2002-2003, the Dialogue on Effective Water Governance took place through country and regional workshops that brought together parliamentarians, government agencies, NGOs, UN agencies, donors, the private sector and other stakeholders. It was agreed that work was to continue to strengthen the water governance initiative. The Dialogue was accepted as a Type II Implementation Partnership at the World Summit on Sustainable Development in Johannesburg and this provides an opportunity to promote effective water governance and concentrate on priority themes and hot topics. The Dialogue has clearly demonstrated that water governance cannot be isolated from development in society at large. There was a general agreement that what is required is to make distributed governance effective.<a href="http://www.gwpforum.org/gwp/library/Effective_Water_Governance.pdf" target="_blank">Read this document. </a></p>
							<p><span class="date">8/09/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Water/Relevant-publications/General/Dialogue-on-Effective-Water-Governance">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
